#create function to get distance from longitude and latitude using 

def Distance_Haversine(lon_start, lat_start, lat_end, lon_end):

    lon_start, lat_start, lat_end, lon_end = map(np.radians, [lon_start, lat_start, lat_end, lon_end])

    lon_diff = np.absolute(lon_end - lon_start)
    lat_diff = np.absolute(lat_end - lat_start)

    
    dist = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(np.sin(lat_diff/2.0)**2 + np.cos(lat_start) * np.cos(lat_end) * np.sin(lon_diff/2.0)**2 ))
    dist_km = (6367 * dist)
    return dist_km

Summary Data Preliminary Wrangling¶

1) transform duration sec to duration min to minimize the diffrence between values and help in making Duration Labels

2) Create Duration_Labels feature which represent a categorical representation of time into 5 categorize which enhancevisualizatoon

3) Use Start and End Station Longitude and Latitude to get Distance covered by users per trip

4) Create Age variable from member birth_year

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 triprides in the dataset with 16 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time , start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_id, start_station_longitude, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip ). Most variables are numeric in nature, but the variables start_time and end_time are date & time and the variables start_station_name, end_station_name, user_type, member_gender are object type and finaly the bike share for all trip feature is of type boolean

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The feature of main intrest is the duration_min and Duration_Labels feature and duration label feature and how they are affected by other features

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The supporting features are the Distance, gender, Age, finaly the user type

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

1) Duration: Duration was presented better using duration labels variable created in wrangling process which helped having better understanding where the duration points lie and how to measure them there was alot of outliers points which was avoided by setting correct limit measured from duration labels which has the most percentage of data.

2) Distance: Distance also had alot of outliers which was observed from the graph after looking closer to the distance variable created and was avoided by setting correct limit that had most of the percentage of data

3) Age: After looking to the line created that represent the age distrbution its clear that age varies between 20 and 80 and high percentage of data lies between 25 - 30 marks a categorical variabel was created which divide age to 3 categories Youth Adutls and Seniors

5) User Type : from this feature we deduced that 91 percent of the people who use variable are Subscribers while 9 percent are customers

6) Gender: 75 percent of users were male, 23 percent female, 2 percent are others

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

age column was added from the member birth year column duration was changed from sec to min then duration labels feature was created which is used to have better visualization to time than old visualization
